'''Daniel McDonald''' (July 30, 1960 <U+2013> February 15, 2007) was an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] who [[Guest appearance|guest-starred]] in many TV shows including ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', and ''[[Sex in the City]]''. He was also involved in [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], performing most recently in ''[[Mamma Mia!]]''.

==Personal life==
McDonald was born the youngest of seven children  and raised in [[Romulus, New York]].  He graduated from [[Ithaca College]].  

McDonald's older brother, [[Christopher McDonald]], is also an actor who is seen in many films and television shows.

He met Mujah Maraini-Melehi during the rehearsals for ''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]''. The couple were married in 1999 and had two children, Fosco and Ondina .<ref name=gans/>

==Career==
He was a life member of the [[Actors Studio]]. He also studied at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]] in London, with Paul Curtis of the [[American Mime Theatre]], and with [[Sanford Meisner]] on the island of [[Bequia]] in the [[British West Indies]] where he met long-time friend and photographer Michael Sanville. 

McDonald received a 1997 [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical|Tony Award]] nomination for his lead role in ''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]'', which co-starred [[Gregory Harrison]].

In 2002, Daniel McDonald replaced Alan Campbell as lead in the national tour of ''[[Contact (musical)|Contact]]''.

''The Gift: Life Unwrapped'', McDonald's last film, was released [[List of works published posthumously|posthumously]] in May 2007.

He recorded an album ''True Love''.  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/Daniel_McDonald_Album_True_Love_to_Be_Released_20080319|title=Broadway World}}</ref> 
==Death==
McDonald died in [[New York]], aged 46, from [[brain cancer]].  

{{quote box |width=30em | bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right  | quote=''[[Steel Pier (musical)|Steel Pier]]'' director [[Scott Ellis]] said in a Feb. 16 [2007] statement, "What made [[Daniel McDonald|Daniel]] so special as a performer was what made him so special as a person. He had an incredible openness, honesty, integrity that made him remarkable both onstage and off."<ref name=gans>{{cite news | last=Simonson | first=Robert| last=Gans | first=Andrew| title=Daniel McDonald, Broadway Musical Actor, Is Dead at 46
